Step 2: Create Azure AD Users

Objective: Create internal users with realistic attributes.

Steps:

Microsoft Entra ID â†’ Users â†’ New user â†’ Create new user

Create at least 3 users, for example:

admin.user

it.support

hr.employee

Configure:

Display name

Username

Job title

Department

Usage location

Save generated passwords securely

Expected Outcome:

Users appear in the Users list

ðŸ“¸ Screenshot: User List

Step 3: Create a Security Group (Assigned Membership)

Objective: Demonstrate manual group-based access control.

Steps:

Microsoft Entra ID â†’ Groups â†’ New group

Group type: Security

Group name: IT-Assigned-SG

Membership type: Assigned

Add one or more users manually

Expected Outcome:

Selected users are members of the group

ðŸ“¸ Screenshot: Assigned Group Members

Step 4: Create a Security Group (Dynamic Membership)

Objective: Demonstrate rule-based group membership.

Steps:

Microsoft Entra ID â†’ Groups â†’ New group

Group type: Security

Group name: IT-Dynamic-SG

Membership type: Dynamic User

Add rule:

(user.department -eq "IT")

Validate and save

Expected Outcome:

Users with Department = IT are automatically added

ðŸ“¸ Screenshot: Dynamic Group Rule

Step 5: Manage Azure AD Guest Users (B2B)

Objective: Invite and manage an external user.

Steps:

Microsoft Entra ID â†’ Users â†’ New user â†’ Invite external user

Enter a valid external email address

Send invitation

Assign guest user to a security group

Expected Outcome:

Guest user listed with User Type = Guest

ðŸ“¸ Screenshot: Guest User Properties

Validation Checklist




Security & Best Practices

Use groups instead of direct user permissions

Apply least privilege access

Separate admin and standard users

Use dynamic groups for scalability

Lessons Learned

Dynamic groups rely on accurate user attributes

Guest users have limited default permissions

Tenant context switching can be confusing for beginners

